MEDICATIONS:

Acetaminophen (generic equivalent of Tylenol or name-brand Tylenol) 500mg up to every 6 hours for mild to moderate pain. Tylenol #3 up to every four hours as needed for severe pain at the arm incision. Do not take more than 2 grams of acetaminophen (Tylenol) from this or other sources in a 24 hour period. Dispose of all unused prescription pain medication pills at CVS or Walgreens within one month of surgery.


Acetaminophen (generic equivalent of Tylenol or name-brand Tylenol) 500mg up to every 6 hours for mild to moderate pain. Tramadol (new prescription added today) up to every four hours as needed for severe pain at the arm incision. Dispose of all unused prescription pain medication pills at CVS or Walgreens within one month of surgery.


Take docusate/senna tablet twice a day to prevent constipation. Constipation is common after operation, both because of the operation itself and also because of medications used for anesthesia.  Preventing constipation can help with pain control. 




PHYSICAL ACTIVITY:
=================
No heavy lifting for 6 weeks. Leave dressing in place until seen in post-operative clinic or by dialysis center for evaluation/training. 

No driving within 48 hours (two days) of either surgery or of using narcotic (prescription) pain medications.

Sponge-bathe only for six weeks. After, may shower if ok'ed by dialysis center. No swimming or bathing (submerging catheter under water). 

 
DIETARY INSTRUCTIONS:
====================
No new dietary restrictions imposed by this procedure.

 
RESOURCES/FOLLOW-UP CARE:
========================

Contact your dialysis center WITHIN THREE BUSINESS DAYS to inform them that you now have a newly-placed peritoneal dialysis catheter. Newly placed catheters should generally be flushed at approximately ONE WEEK after surgery. It can generally be used for normal peritoneal dialysis at two weeks after surgery.




